title: For Trade:  Vintage 1927 Photographs - Native American Portraits by T.J. Hileman
postcontent:
They are beautiful T.J. Hileman original photographs from the 1920's and are portraits of Blackfoot Native Americans. Both photographs will be in identical frames. (I am in the process of picking up a 2nd frame for the unframed photograph) Both photographs have T.J. Hilemans, stamp imprinted down towards either the bottom right or left corner of the photo. It says "Hileman" and it's done in a way you can feel the imprint like it's raised on the photo side and indented on the underside. They also both have some writing on the back that describes the subject matter on the front and have the date of 1927. A couple of the other photographs from my collection, had similar writing on the back, but they also had a stamp by Glacier National Park, and wording to the effect of this photo is by T.J. Hileman, copyright. I had a total of 5 Hileman photographs all from the 1920's. I really only want to keep 1 or 2, and I just sold 2 of them this month. So I am willing to part with 1 or maybe 2 of my remaining 3 photographs.

I am looking for $300-$350 each in trade. If you do some research you will find Hileman photo's of Native American's only come up for auction every couple years, so they are hard to find. I found about 6-8 examples over the past decade that have sold in auctions and the auction prices varied from $250 on the low end up to $1,200 at the highest (to be honest that was quite a lot, more than double any of the other photographs except for one signed by the Chief that was pictured in the portrait) T.J. Hileman lived in Kalispell, Montana near Glacier National Park, and was know for his photographs of Glacier National Park and the Blackfoot Native American Indians.(quite a few Glacier National Park postcards from 1911-1940 would have been photographs taken by Hileman) He was also the official photographer for the Great Northern Railroad. 

I also have a half a dozen railroad calendars from the late 1920's and the 1930's with artwork depicting Blackfoot Native American's by Winold Reiss of New York. (I am in the process of taking photographs of these currently, but email me if interested)

Please feel free to email me any ?'s

I would also include some cash towards a trade depending on the deal.

I am interested in selling/trading a tandem axle car hauler that I rarely use. I bought it used two years ago when I was buying broken down vehicles to part out on the side but now I really have no need for it. Although the car hauler is a little smaller than normal (13' Long x 6.5' Wide) it will actually accommodate large trucks and SUV's without a problem. As you can see in the pictures below, the car hauler has an extended neck so, unlike many other car hauler designs, you can pull a vehicle all the way to the front of this one and let the bumper extend over the neck. In addition, this car hauler has two other design features that I love: it gently slopes at the back (to allow you to load vehicles that sit lower to the ground) and it has wheel guides welded from front to back (which help you keep vehicles straight when loading them).  Overall, this car hauler is in excellent condition both cosmetically and mechanically. postcontent:
To all the people complaining about prices: The prices are driven by lopsided supply and demand driven by the professional parasites in Washington DC like Dianne Feinstein and Obama who never miss a chance to exploit tragedy to strip people of their rights. There is absolutely NO problem that these people cannot make worse. Of course, THEY don't need guns because THEY are protected 24/7 by ARMED security details. Your safety and ability to defend yourself and your family, is of less concern to them than taking advantage of every available opportunity to grandstand on the backs of crime victims.

If you want to actually do something about it then contact your elected officials, that's at a minimum, your rep and both senators. If you don't know who they are then look them up here:

http://www.nraila.org/get-involved-locally/grassroots/write-your-reps.aspx

If you want boiler plate for an email message here's a suggestion:

Dear,

I am writing you regarding the numerous gun control schemes currently being proposed. Guns are not the problem. If guns or access to guns were the problem, then Vermont, with some of the most lenient gun laws in the country, which doesn't even require a permit to carry concealed, would not consistently have some of the lowest homicide rates in the nation. Just 1.1 homicides / per 100,000 population in 2010, which was about 1/4 of the national average. So much for argument that availability of guns increases homicide rates. 

With regard to "assault weapons", which are really just semi-automatic rifles; these guns are rarely used in homicides. For example in 2011, according to the FBI Uniform Crime Reports, rifles, including "assault" rifles were used in 2.55% of homicides. The UCR does not track how many of these specifically involved an "assault" rifle, however, it is obviously less than 2.55% for 2011 since that is the total for ALL rifles combined. By contrast personal weapons (hands, fists, feet, etc.) were used as the murder weapon in 5.75% of homicides in 2011 and knives and cutting instruments were used in 13.38% of homicides. Other years are similar. 

The UCR 2007 - 2011 homicide by weapon tables are here: 

www.fbi.gov/about-us/cjis/ucr/crime-in-the-u.s/2011/crime-in-the-u.s.-2011/tables/expanded-homicide-data-table-8 

There is simply too little criminal use of these so called "assault" weapons which are really just semi-automatic rifles used lawfully by millions of Americans, for regulation of them to make any difference in our crime rates even if criminals obeyed laws, and, they don't. Connecticut had a 'gun free' schools law and an 'assault weapons' ban. Neither had any effect on the school shooter there, other than perhaps to guarantee his success by insuring that he was the only one armed. Compare the Sandy Hook tragedy, where nobody but the killer was armed, to the 1997 Pearl Mississippi school shooting where Vice Principal Joel Myrick was able to retrieve his handgun from his truck (it was illegal for him to possess or carry it in the school) and apprehend the shooter, Luke Woodham without Myrick firing a single shot. Luke Woodham's admitted plan after attacking his high school, was to go  to the local Jr. High and continue his rampage there. Myrick stopped that plan cold. Unfortunately, there was no ARMED Joel Myrick at Sandy Hook. 

We don't need more gun control, which has failed over and over every time it's been tried. We need real security, not useless 'feel good' measures that strip us of our constitutional rights for the mere illusion of safety. We need ARMED police officers in schools. These officers can provide security from all levels of threats as well as serve as badly needed role models for the children they protect. Giving the Joel Myricks of our country the ability to legally possess the guns they need to responsibly protect themselves and the children in their care wouldn't hurt either.
